An [`ArrayBuffer`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/ArrayBuffer) cannot be accessed directly and you can use [`TypedArray`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/TypedArray) views or [`DataView`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/DataView) objects to manipulate the buffer&#39;s byte values. You can use [`TextEncoder`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/TextEncoder) and [`TextDecoder`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/TextDecoder) for easier manipulation of text backed by ArrayBuffers.

Consider using [`fetch()`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Fetch_API), which is more performant that the older `XMLHttpRequest` ways.  An `ArrayBuffer` must be serialized to a string to send in an HTTP request.  

    const encoder = new TextEncoder();
    const encoded = encoder.encode(&#39;hello&#39;);
    const serialized = encoded.toString();
    fetch(&#39;https://example.com&#39;, {
      method: &#39;post&#39;,
      body: serialized
    })

