Vue component methods are bound to the context, which is component instance. This could be checked with:

    function foo() {
        foo() {
            console.log(this);
        }
    
    }

    ...
    methods: { foo },
    created() {
        this.foo !== foo // true
    }
    ...


`this.foo.bind === Function.prototype.bind` check isn&#39;t representative since `this.foo` is regular function, so it inherits `bind`.

Once a function is bound, it cannot be re-bound or be called with different context:

    const context = {};
    const boundFoo = (function foo() { return this; }).bind(context);
    // boundFoo.call({}) === context
    // boundFoo.bind({})() === context

It isn&#39;t a good practice to rely on arbitrary dynamic `this` context in JS OOP. If a method needs a context, it should be provided to it as an argument:

    methods: {
        foo(ctx) {
            console.log(ctx);
        }
    },
    created() {
        this.foo({ bar: 42 });
    }

Or be shared as instance property, depending on the purpose.

